{{Infobox person | name = Albert Avdolyan | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|11|8|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Krasnodar]], Russia | residence = Moscow and [[Beverly Hills, California]] | citizenship = Russian and Maltese | alma_mater = | occupation = Chairman of [[Expatel]] | networth = | spouse = Elena Avdolyan | children = 4 | website = [http://www.expatel.ru/ Expatel Web Site] | footnotes = }}
'''Albert Avdolyan''' (born 8 November 1970), is a Russian-Armenian businessman. In 2016 acquired Maltese citizenship through its citizenship for investment scheme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://daphnecaruanagalizia.com/2016/08/russian-telecoms-mogul-lives-19m-beverly-hills-mansion-estate-buys-malteseeu-passports-family-six/|title=Russian telecoms mogul who lives in $30m Beverly Hills mansion estate buys Maltese/EU passports for himself, wife and four children - Daphne Caruana Galizia's Notebook - Running Commentary|author=|date=18 August 2016|website=daphnecaruanagalizia.com|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> He is specialized in the [[telecommunication]] sector. He is the founder and owner of Mobile [[WiMAX]] company [[Expatel]] and a shareholder of [[Yota]], and is considered as one of the key players of [[4G]] technology in Russia.<ref>[http://www.groundreport.com/Business/How-Russia-became-a-Wimax-superpower How Russia became a Wimax superpower], Groundreport</ref>
==Early career and personal life== In 1999, Avdolyan acquired 15% of the shares of Russian chemical company Usoliekhimprom.<ref>[http://ea.ruschamber.net/eng/card.php?cat=21664&pcat=0&crumbtitle=IRBI%20member%20search Usoliekhimport] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324035110/http://ea.ruschamber.net/eng/card.php?cat=21664&pcat=0&crumbtitle=IRBI%20member%20search |date=2012-03-24 }}, Russian Chamber</ref> Since 2003, he has also been a shareholder of construction equipment firm Gazkomplektservice, a subsidiary of [[Gazprom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neftegazkomplekt.en.hisupplier.com/|title=Russian Federation mazut Trading Company - Nefte Gaz Komplekt Ltd|author=|date=|website=neftegazkomplekt.en.hisupplier.com|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref>
Avdolyan is married and is the father of four children. In 2009, he and his wife bought a home in Beverly Hills.<ref>[http://losangeles.blockshopper.com/property/4348016035/1108_tower Albert Avdolyan buying agreement], Blockshopper</ref> In 2011, he bought a second house in the [[Beverly Park]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redfin.com/CA/Beverly-Hills/50-Beverly-Park-Way-90210/home/6834082|title=50 Beverly Park Way, Beverly Hills, CA 90210|first=|last=Redfin|date=|website=Redfin|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> This home was heavily damaged by a fire in the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/news/ci_20979448/beverly-hills-mansion-fire-causes-more-than-1|title=Beverly Hills mansion fire causes more than $1 million in damage to former ‘Real Housewives’ home|author=|date=30 June 2012|website=dailynews.com|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref>
==Expatel== In October 2009, Avdolyan<ref>[http://cplash.com/post/How-Albert-Avdolyan-Became-a-Key-Player-of-Russian-Internet-business676.html How Albert Avdolyan became a key player in Russian Internet business], Cplash</ref> founded Russian company Expatel,<ref>[http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/8289888-albert-avdolyan-expatels-4g-success-story Albert Avdolyan Expatel's 4G success story] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227174817/http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/8289888-albert-avdolyan-expatels-4g-success-story |date=2011-02-27 }}, Allvoices</ref> one of the Russian leaders in Mobile WiMAX (G4) Internet technology.
In 2010, Expatel had more than 500 retail offices across Russia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expatel.ru/o-kompanii/istoriya|title=Expatel Official website|author=|date=|website=expatel.ru|accessdate=8 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715231153/http://www.expatel.ru/o-kompanii/istoriya|archive-date=2011-07-15|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> and was the first Russian company to supply optical fiber services to its customers.
