{{infobox person | name=Hector Estrada | image= | caption= | nationality=Puerto Rican | occupation=Entrepreneur, Creative Director | known_for=Triko, Amivectio }}
'''Hector Estrada''' is a Puerto Rican and Dominican entrepreneur and creative director.<ref name=club>{{cite web| url=http://www.clubplanet.com/sidekick3dwade/night_ballin/fashion/triko_clothing_the_art_of_life.html| title=Triko Clothing: The Art of Life| author=Navani Otero| publisher=Club Planet| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=qc>{{cite web| url=http://www.qconline.com/life/designer-creates-eco-friendly-fashions/article_08006f6e-f870-5e1c-b0f2-5fe94580b8ae.html| title=Designer creates eco-friendly fashions| date=September 8, 2007| publisher=QCOnline| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=Triko for MTV3 Fashionista + Interview with Hector Estrada| journal=MTV}}</ref> He owns the brands Triko<ref name=tree>{{cite web| url=http://www.treehugger.com/style/triko-streetwear-with-a-soul.html| title=Triko: Streetwear With a Soul| author=Erin Courtenay| date=September 14, 2007| publisher=Treehugger| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=fashion>{{cite web| url=http://www.fashionledge.com/articles/07/Jan-Feb/art_of_life/index.php| title=The Art of Life| author=Yvette N. Coleman| publisher=Fashion Edge| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> and Amivectio.
==Career== Estrada began working for [[Eckō Unltd.]] while he was still in college,<ref name=club/> and graduated from [[New Jersey City University]].<ref name=qc/> He has also worked as creative director for the brand MeccaUSA.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fibre2fashio.com/news/company-news/polyone-corporation/newsdetails.aspx?news_id=72508| title=Mecca Launches Mecca Moda; Label Seeks Mature Customers With a Higher-Priced Line and a Sophisticated Point of View| date=November 19, 2001| publisher=Daily News Record| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> In 2001, he launched his brand Triko.<ref name=club/> Triko incorporates sustainable materials such as [[Phytelephas|tagua]], coconut shell and organic cotton in its clothing.<ref name=tree/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fibre2fashio.com/news/company-news/polyone-corporation/newsdetails.aspx?news_id=72508| title=Green is In: Eco-Friendly Fashion from Triko| date=September 5, 2007| author=Steven Volynets| publisher=Good Clean Tech| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> The name "Triko" is a combination of the words "Tri", completion comes in three, "K" from "Arawak" meaning good person, and "O" for "one" referring to unity.<ref name=fashion/> In 2005, Estrada partnered with [[Reebok]] to make a Triko sneaker which was inspired by the Mexican Revolution.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.sportswearnet.com/fashionnews/pages/protected/TRIKO--REEBOK-LAUNCH-SNEAKER-COLLABORATION_198.html| title=Triko & Reebok Launch Sneaker Collaboration| date=March 14, 2005| publisher=Sportswear International| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref> Estrada supports children's charities through Triko, including contributions to [[Child Soldiers International|Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers]], and the [[Children's Aid Society]]. Three percent of all Triko sales go to child-based charities.<ref name=fibre>{{cite web| url=http://www.fibre2fashio.com/news/textiles-technology-news/newsdetails.aspx?news_id=116731| title=Triko adopts Virtual Piggy technologies for online payments| date=October 10, 2012| publisher=Fibre 2 Fashion| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>
In 2009, Estrada introduced his brand, Amivectio. The brand aims to define modern America by combining classic fashion with innovation and functionality.<ref name=fibre/> Amivectio is a combination of [[amicus curiae|"amicus,"]] meaning friends, and "circumvectio," meaning revolt, which combined means "Friends of the Revolution." Amivectio aims to challenge and alter society through six principles: equal opportunity, clean air, water, soil, and energy, health and sustainability, and education. The label supports the [[Clean Water Action]], an organization which works to protect America's waters, build healthy communities, and support democracy.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fibre2fashio.com/news/textiles-technology-news/newsdetails.aspx?news_id=116731| title=Amivectio: Community-Inspired Streetwear| date=May 28, 2009| author=Asmara Wreksono| publisher=Sojones| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>
Both of Estrada's brands, Triko and Amivectio, were featured at the Cargo Tradeshow in 2010.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://live.drjays.com/index.php/2010/01/17/style-report-inside-fashions-tradeshow-season/| title=Style Report: Inside Fashion’s Tradeshow Season| author=Mel Peralta| date=January 17, 2010| publisher=DrJays| accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>
